# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bicycle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bicycle/27-5-mountain-bike] Names for the wheel size other than the ISO designated 56-584 are **27.5"** and **650B**, both considered controversial marketing terms.
[src:bicycle/27-5-mountain-bike] The 27.5 inch are seen as a compromise between the two existing standards of the original 26 inch (ISO 559 mm rim) and recently emerged 29 inch (ISO 622 mm rim) mountain bikes (late 2000s).
[src:bicycle/27-5-mountain-bike] In 2007, 27.5 inch wheels for mountain bike use was pioneered by Kirk Pacenti as the optimal choice for full suspension mountain bikes, and in 2013 at least 10 companies had launched models with 27.5 inch wheels, with some parts manufacturers following suit.
[src:bicycle/27-5-mountain-bike] In 2012, Nino Schurter won the World Cup event at Pietermaritzburg, South Africa, and placed second in the Olympics in 2012 on 27.5 inch wheels.
[src:bicycle/27-5-mountain-bike] In 2022, author Paul Tuthill at Conquer The Bike stated that 27.5 inch wheels were "all but dead, [but] still remains on life support", with 29ers being more common for downhill and endurance riding, and 26ers being more popular for regular bike riding, mountain biking and dirt jumping.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] 29er rims have an interior diameter of 622 millimetres (24.5 in) and the average 29″ mountain bike tire is (in ISO notation) 59-622 – corresponding to an outside diameter of about 29.15 inches (740 mm).
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] The typical 26″ MTB tire has a rim diameter of 559 millimetres (22.0 in) and an outside tire diameter of about 26 inches (660 mm).
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] In the early 1980s, the size of the wheels for the emerging mountain bikes was undecided.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] So when English off-road cycling pioneer Geoff Apps contacted Gary Fisher and Charlie Kelly with news that he had built a prototype off-road bicycle that used large-diameter 28 × 1¾ (ISO 47-622), 47mm wide Nokian Hakkapeliitta snow tires from Finland, they were intrigued.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] However the bicycle marketed as the Aventura by Apps' own company, Cleland Cycles Ltd, between 1982 and 1984 used the more readily available Nokian Hakkapeliitta 26 × 2 (ISO 54-584).
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] The 650B size, also known as 27.5″, reappeared in 2007 as a compromise between the 26 inch and 29 inch sizes.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] The name "29er" comes from a bicycle called the Two Niner, which was offered by the Fisher bike company in 2001, according to 1998 Mountain Bike Hall of Fame inductee Don Cook.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] The US division of Bianchi Bicycles offered a line of 29″ wheeled off-road bikes beginning in 1991 called the Project bikes.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Their 1992 product catalog raved about the advantages of the larger wheels and showed three different bikes, the Project 3, 5 and 7.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Likewise, in 1991 Panaracer developed a 700c version of the Smoke Tire for OEM use on the Diamondback Overdrive and Overdrive Comp mountain bikes.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] The original company Klein produced a small quantity of a 29″ wheeled version of their successful "Attitude" MTB racer, and named it the Adept.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] It failed to find a market and was discontinued.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] A key product release, the first true 29″ tire, was produced by an early supporter of the 29″ movement Wilderness Trail Bikes.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] The company introduced the first true 29″ tire, the Nanoraptor, in 1999.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] At about the same time, White Brothers produced the first commercially available 29″ suspension forks.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Before then suspension forks used were forks designed for trekking bikes or hybrids.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] For many years, 29″ frames and bikes were usually only available from small little-known manufactures like Niner Bikes.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Surly Bikes introduced their 29″ frameset, the Karate Monkey, in 2002.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Gary Fisher Bicycles, a division of Trek Bicycles, became the first of the major manufactures to offer a line of 29″ bikes.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Their lines never sold well until the introduction of single-speed 29″ bike the Rig, in 2004.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Today, most bicycle manufacturers in the US market offer at least one 29″ bicycle or frame.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] A tire with a tread width of less than 2.0 in (51 mm) in width is sometimes considered a cyclocross tire by 29″ enthusiasts, even though in cyclocross any tire wider than 1.5 in (38 mm) is not a cyclocross tire.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Although they are both intended for off-road use, and typically use a 622 mm rim, cyclocross bikes and 29″ wheeled MTBs differ in their basic handling and geometry, construction methods, durability, and intended lifespan.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Bikes exist that blur the distinction by combining attributes of both, however.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] One example of this is a Monstercross bike, often using a standard mountain bike frame intended for use with 26″ wheels with 700c wheels and 700 × 38c-45c tires, disc or cantilever brakes, MTB or cross gearing, and the drop bars of a cyclocross bike.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] The advantages and disadvantages of 29ers are often debated in the mountain bike community.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Disadvantages of the 29″ wheel include added weight, perceived sluggishness in handling, and problems with fit (specifically, front wheel/toe overlap and high standover height).
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Advantages include reduced rolling resistance , perceived increased stability while retaining quick handling, and an enhanced ability to roll over obstacles.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] One item that is often raised is tire contact patch size and shape.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] All else being equal, such as tire width, rim width, inflation pressure and rider weight, the contact patch of a 29″ wheel has the same area and is slightly longer (~5%) than that of a 26″ wheel.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Most of these claims have yet to be objectively investigated.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Small scale, unpublished studies (including one done by Pepperdine University, reportedly at the request of Gary Fisher) exist but both proponents and detractors of 29″ wheels are generally unimpressed with their scientific rigor.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Long debates over how to conduct a "fair" test of the efficiency of 29″ vs 26″ mountain bikes have raged online, but no serious efforts have been made to conduct a large-scale, scientific study.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] One variation is to have a 29″ front wheel and a 26″ rear wheel (commonly called a "96er").
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Using the smaller rear wheel allows shorter and quicker handling frames, more options for rear suspension designs and lighter bicycle weight.
[src:bicycle/29er-bicycle] Another variation is to have a 26″ front wheel with a 29″ rear wheel (commonly called a "69er" though Trek introduced a "69er" in 2007 with a 29″ front wheel and a 26″ rear wheel).
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] 3T switched production to carbon-fiber composite materials and in 2008 returned to pro cycling after several years' absence.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] For the 2008 season it sponsored the CSC–Saxo Bank team which won the Tour de France.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] 3T sponsored three pro teams; Garmin–Slipstream, Cervélo TestTeam and Team Milram for the 2009 professional season.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] In 2013 3T was a sponsor for BMC Racing Team.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] 3T debuted its first "gravel" bicycle in June 2016, and followed with their second the year after.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] 3T is the manufacturing partner for all models of BMW branded bicycles.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] 3T was founded by Mario Dedioniggi in Turin in 1961.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] It is located in Bergamo and originally known as 3TTT—Tecnologia del Tubo Torino (Turin Tube Technology).
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] In 1970, 3T switched production to aluminum alloy in place of steel, to cut down on weight.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] By the late 1990s, 3T started using carbon-fiber composites.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] For the 2008 season, 3T sponsored Team CSC.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] The team's World Champion time trialist, Fabian Cancellara, rode it during the Tour of California.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] During the European season at the Giro d'Italia, CSC's team failed to win the race's opening Team Time Trial.
[src:bicycle/3t-cycling] For the 2009 season, 3T sponsored three professional teams: Cervélo TestTeam, Garmin Slipstream, and Milram.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The **A-bike** is a folding bicycle released by Sir Clive Sinclair in the United Kingdom on 12 July 2006.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] It was designed by Hong Kong design agency Daka, in collaboration with Sinclair Research, over a 5-year period.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] Clive Sinclair envisioned the A-bike, and Alex Kalogroulis was the main designer.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The first version had 15 cm (6 in) wheels, which was increased to 20 cm (8 in) in later models.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] In 2015, an electric version, the A-Bike Electric, was introduced to the public as part of a Kickstarter campaign.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The A-bike was designed by Sinclair Research, in collaboration with Hong Kong design agency Daka, over a 5-year period.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] Clive Sinclair envisioned the A-bike, and Alex Kalogroulis was the main design engineer.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] It was released on 12 July 2006, and was priced at £199.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The official Europe distributor, Mayhem UK, hoped to sell 25,000 units in the first 12 months.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] By 2007 it was being noted that a "large number of counterfeit" A-bikes were appearing in China and elsewhere.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] Early reviews praised the A-bike for being lightweight and easy to fold, but noted the flexing frame and uncomfortable saddle, and criticised the tiny wheels for being unsafe on uneven roads.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] In 2008 the Mark-II version was released: officially known as the **A-Bike Plus**.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] This version had strengthened aluminium tubing, a new air-sprung cushioned saddle, and an upgraded drive mechanism.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The Mark-III version was released in 2010, and was officially known as the **A-Bike City**.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The main changes were larger 20 cm (8 in) wheels and it was priced at £299.99.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The A-bike is a small wheel bicycle with 15 cm (6 in) wheels, increasing to 20 cm (8 in) in later models.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The original model weighs 5.7 kg (13 lb), and folds to 67×30×16 cm (26.4×11.8×6.3 in) reducing its volume to about 25% of its original size.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] A twin-chain system enables the bike to travel about 3.2 m (10.5 ft) per crank rotation despite the bicycle's small-diameter wheels (15 cm (6 in)).
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The crankcase housing almost completely encloses the drive mechanism, protecting it and preventing oil stains on clothing or floor surfaces.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] In November 2006, A-bike was featured on UK television programme *The Gadget Show*, alongside the Strida.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The distribution company behind the A-bike was featured on the UK Television programme Badger or Bust broadcast on 5 June 2007.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] Richard Hammond and James May carried A-bikes in their suitcases and unfolded them to bike from a ferry dock to a cable car.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] In 2015, an electric version, the **A-Bike Electric**, was introduced to the public as part of a Kickstarter campaign.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The design featured 20 cm (8 in) wheels, as well as a larger seat and sturdier frame.
[src:bicycle/a-bike] The funding campaign was successful and production began before the end of the year.
[src:bicycle/abici] The founders formed the prototype for Abici bicycles in Lombardy using the 1950s catalog of an Italian craftsman.
[src:bicycle/abici] Their goal was a classic bicycle with high-tech details and a vintage aesthetic.
[src:bicycle/abici] The name Abici derives from "bici", the Italian slang for "bicicletta".
[src:bicycle/abici] The name also refers to the first three letters of the Italian alphabet: A-B-C.
[src:bicycle/abici] Abici bikes are made in eight colors based on car colors of the 1950s, has a Brooks England saddle with copper rivets, metal mudguards and a chrome brake rod.
[src:bicycle/abici] The light-weight bikes are made from aluminum, carbon fiber and titanium.
[src:bicycle/abici] The company produces classic style bikes, including touring bikes for men and women, as well as racing and mountain bikes.
[src:bicycle/abici] Each bicycle is handmade and tested in Italy.
[src:bicycle/abici] They come in five models: Granturismo, Camporella, Sveltina, Amante and Fuga.
[src:bicycle/abici] In 2009, Abici and Italian fashion house Fendi created the *Fendi Abici Amante Donna Bicycle*, featuring Fendi's *Selleria* leather accessories and fur saddlebags.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Public policies promoting active mobility tend to improve health indicators by increasing the levels of physical fitness and reducing the rates of obesity and diabetes, whilst also reducing the consumption of fossil fuels and consequent carbon emissions.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] These policies are proven to result in large increases in active transportation for commuting: for example Portland, Oregon, was able to increase bicycle use 5-fold from 1990 to 2009 with pro-cycling programs.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Studies have shown that city level programs are more effective than encouraging active mobility on the individual level.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Health benefits of active mobility include alleviating urban pressures, reduced energy consumption and production, and improved quality of life.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Commonly active transport prevents the chances of fatal disease rooted from pollution and environmental issues.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Active mobility improves health by decreasing air pollution from cars.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] However, negative health problems can arise from inactive and sedentary lifestyles.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The US Centers for Disease Control recommends increasing access to active transportation.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Multiple U.S. studies advocate for increased access to active transportation for everyone, including children, due to multiple health benefits.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Sedentary people can lower their BMI by increasing physical activity.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] A House of Commons of the United Kingdom Health Committee report about Obesity in 2004 recommended cycling and walking as key components to combat obesity.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Public Health England estimated in 2016 that in the UK, physical inactivity directly contributes to one in six deaths every year.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The PHE report notes that walking and cycling daily is effective to increase physical activity and reduce levels of obesity, as well as prevent cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, cancer and several mental illnesses, including depression.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Physical exercise improves mental and physical health.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Cyclists and walkers perceive their environment differently than people driving in cars because cars block sensory inputs that active mobility exposes.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Proponents of active mobility assert that activities like cycling and walking promote a feeling of community and connection, improving mental health and overall wellbeing.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Providing good infrastructure for active mobility effectively promotes this type of transportation to decrease traffic and urban congestion.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Cycling and walking can save money by reducing money spent on gasoline.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Consequences of cycling and walking include increased exposure to air pollution, noise, and more frequent accidents.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Cycling reduces the need for large roads and parking lots as bikes occupy 8% of available space compared to cars.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] As cycling and walking increases, urban infrastructure can be transformed to parks to add green space to urban environments.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Aesthetically pleasing areas can become optimal places for walking and cycling in cities.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Urban environments can also be transformed into walkable areas, which can benefit the elderly, but safety can be problematic if areas are congested with cars.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Designing safe walkable areas in cities can increase the popularity of walking, decrease physical inactivity, and improve health.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Additionally, electric bike users benefit from this type of physical activity.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] In seven European cities, electric bike users had 10% higher weekly energy expenditure than other cyclists.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] People switching to e-bike from either private cars or public transport expend more energy as physical activity increases, gaining between 550 and 880 Metabolic Equivalent Task minutes per week.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Electric bikes may act as a cycling enabler for women.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] An environmental benefit of active mobility is reducing greenhouse gas emissions to slow global warming.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Every year, a typical car emits 4.6 metric tons of carbon dioxide.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] As a greenhouse gas, carbon dioxide in the atmosphere speeds up the effects of climate change.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] As automobile use increases greenhouse gas emissions, the rates in which our Earth is reaching climate tipping point thresholds are escalating.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Active mobility lowers daily greenhouse gas emissions, slowing these tipping points.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] For example, in New Zealand, active mobility has been found to reduce emissions of carbon dioxide by 1% annually.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] In a study of 7 European cities, it was found that individual changes in active travel come with significant lifecycle carbon emissions benefits, even in European urban contexts with already high walking and cycling shares.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] An increase in cycling or walking consistently and independently decreased mobility-related lifecycle CO 2 emissions.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] An average person cycling 1 trip/day more and driving 1 trip/day less for 200 days a year would decrease mobility-related lifecycle CO 2 emissions by about 0.5 tonnes over a year.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Air and noise pollution are negative effects of vehicular transport.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Air pollution negatively affects human health and the environment.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Air pollution can cause acid rain, eutrophication, haze, wildlife deaths, thinning of Earth's ozone layer, crop damage, and global climate change.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Noise pollution disrupts ecosystems and wildlife.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Active mobility reduces air and noise pollution by substituting for cars that produce greenhouse gases and noise, benefiting the environment and urban ecosystems.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Active mobility has appealed to policymakers because of its beneficial contributions to physical health and reductions of air pollution, leading to legislative efforts to make cycling and walking safer and more attractive for commuting and personal errands.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] These measures include infrastructure changes to accommodate more cyclists and pedestrians on roads, regulations to limit car traffic, and education and training to improve the coordination between motor vehicles and individuals using active mobility.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Infrastructure developments that have been correlated with increased active mobility are wider sidewalks, street lighting, flat terrain, and urban greenery, particularly with access to parks.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Several researchers have also emphasized that the largest contribution to active mobility comes from easy access to local amenities such as restaurants, shops, and theaters, which can be promoted by local governments.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] A significant concern about increased active mobility is a corresponding increase in injuries and deaths, especially between pedestrians or cyclists and motor vehicles.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Active mobility may often be more time-consuming than commuting by vehicle, and the effects of distance, geographic features such as hills, and climate may make outdoor exertion uncomfortable or impractical.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Another criticism of active transportation policy contends that converting traffic lanes for bicycle use makes travel more difficult for commuters who must a motor vehicle.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The European Union's Mobility and Transport organization includes the promotion of walking and cycling among its strategies to enable more sustainable transportation in Europe.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The European Union has also adopted a Vision Zero goal to eliminate all traffic deaths, seeking to mitigate the number of incidents between pedestrians and cyclists and motor vehicles, as these commonly result in serious injury or death.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Separate from the European Union, several European cities and regions founded an organization, Polis, in 1989 to coordinate efforts between local governments and the European Union to improve the efficiency of transportation.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] This includes the facilitation of active mobility, which Polis states provides benefits to the environment and to the public's physical health and asserts that these improvements contribute to the economy as well.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Polis recommends that policy decisions should account for benefits from reduced health and environmental costs from active mobility, increased city accessibility from reduced congestion and pollution, and consider regulations on vehicle design to address concerns of safety and convenience.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Polis encourages the development of Sustainable Urban Mobility Plans (SUMPs) to guide mobility projects in cities of all sizes.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Active mobility is used widely in the Netherlands, comprising more than 40% of commuting in urban areas.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The flat topography and temperate climate of the Netherlands benefits active mobility, which has been supported by government policy for decades, including 35,000 kilometers of dedicated cycling paths.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] As a result, the Dutch government estimates that there are about 1.3 bikes per person in the Netherlands.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] A consequence of this is that about 20% of Dutch road accident fatalities are cyclists, with more than 100 cyclists perishing each year.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] This rate and number are higher than most other European countries, reflecting the high use of active mobility in the Netherlands.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] However, policy efforts by the Ministry of Industry and Water Management may have contributed to a declining mortality rate, which fell more than 30% from 2007 to 2016.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The Land Transport Authority (LTA) of Singapore pursues a stated goal to supplement mechanized transportation methods with "walk and cycle options".
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Following a test plan implemented in the neighborhood of Tampines, the Minister of Transport presented a National Cycling Plan in 2013 to provide paths to integrate cycling with Singapore's extensive Mass Rapid Transit system.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] This includes 190 kilometers of paths, thousands of bicycle parking racks, signage, and cyclist education.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] These efforts have been criticized, however, as being limited in scope, especially for limiting the expansion of cycling access to off-road connections, such as through the Park Connectors Network, rather than more infrastructure for commuting in cities.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The UK Government's plan for active travel in England was released in 2020 and is known as *Gear Change*.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The plan aims to make England a 'great cycling nation'.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The plan aims to create cycling and walking corridors, introduce more low-traffic neighbourhoods and school streets, aims to set high standards for cycling infrastructure.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The plan accompanies £2 billion in additional funding over the following five years for cycling and walking announced in May 2020.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The plan also introduced a new body and inspectorate known as Active Travel England.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Scottish Government policy aims to increase the use of active travel modes in Scotland for shorter journeys and to make active mobility safer and inclusive.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The National Walking Strategy was published in 2017 and the Cycling Action Plan for Scotland (CAPS) was last updated in 2017.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The active travel advocacy group Cycling UK criticised the Scottish Government for not increasing funding for active travel.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The Scottish budget allocates £100 million for cycling and walking, which is 3.3% of the transport budget or the total cost of three miles of the A9 dualling scheme.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Within the public sector in Scotland the transport sector has the lowest percentage of women in senior posts.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Only 6.25% of heads of transport bodies are women.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Other steps include the *Active Travel (Wales) Act 2013,* which passed in 2013.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The act requires local authorities to continuously improve facilities and routes for pedestrians and cyclists and to prepare maps identifying current and potential future routes for their use.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] It also requires road improvement and development projects to consider the needs of pedestrians and cyclists at the design stage.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Residents of the United States use active mobility as a mode of transportation less often than residents of other countries.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The far greater mortality rates of pedestrians and cyclists in U.S. cities has been cited as a contributing factor to this trend.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Efforts to increase use of active mobility have been undertaken at the federal levels by the U.S.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Department of Transportation, which pursues the development of active commuting through its Livability Initiative.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Funding increases for these programs, such as the Fixing America's Surface Transportation (FAST) act of 2015, have garnered bipartisan support.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Multiple cities in the United States, including Seattle, Chicago, Minneapolis, Sacramento, and Houston, have implemented their own policies to encourage the active mobility for commuting to work and to school.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] More extensive efforts involve detailed active transportation programs (ATPs), such as those implemented in California, Portland, Oregon, Fort Worth, Texas, and San Diego County.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] However, these efforts have struggled to promote measurable changes in the percentage of commuters using active transportation to work: in the United States Census Bureau's American Community Survey, 3.4% of Americans biked or walked to work in 2013, and only 3.1% did so in 2018.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] People with disabilities often face more issues with active transport than those without disabilities.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Some people have medical barriers to active travel.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] There are some instances where it is not possible for a person to walk or cycle, and, even if the physical, societal and financial barriers were removed, some would still need access to a motor vehicle.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] For those who wish to cycle, barriers can include narrow cycle lanes, infrastructure that requires a cyclist to dismount, physical access barriers and a lack of suitable cycle parking facilities.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] In some cities and countries women lead the way when it comes to walking.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] 54% of journeys completed wholly on foot in London are made by women.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] According to research into gender differences in active travel across a range of international cities, women are more likely than men to walk and more likely to use public transport.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] The gender differences in active travel metrics are age dependent.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Women's and men's perception of danger and safety offer differential travel experience.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Research highlights the importance of a gendered approach towards healthy living and active transport policy making with considerations for reducing road traffic danger and male violence.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Men are more likely to have access to private cars than women.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Design that benefits cars over other modes of transport disproportionately benefits men.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Men and women tend to have different patterns of journeys.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Women are more likely to be trip chaining, and trip chaining encourages car use.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] Women are also more likely to be 'encumbered' by carrying children, shopping or accompanied by elderly companions In the UK fewer women cycle than men and road safety is cited as a concern relating to cycling and to walking.
[src:bicycle/active-mobility] A Sustrans report in the UK found a lack of evidence that women participate in creating transport policy and planning.
[src:bicycle/alan] ALAN was founded in 1972 by Falconi Lodovico, an engineer who had worked for bicycle manufacturer Torpado.
[src:bicycle/alan] The name ALAN comes from the first two letters of Lodovico's children, Alberto and Annamaria.
[src:bicycle/alan] It was the first company to introduce an all aluminium bicycle frame made from aerospace grade aluminum.
[src:bicycle/alan] In 1976, ALAN was again first in developing and manufacturing a production carbon frame made by bonding Torayca carbon fibre composite tubing to cast aluminium lugs.
[src:bicycle/alan] This is a process still widely used today by many manufacturers.
[src:bicycle/alan] Over the years the firm's frames were ridden to 20 cyclo-cross world championships titles, 5 track world championships titles, numerous one-day classics wins, as well as Grand Tour stage wins.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A **bicycle**, also called a **pedal cycle**, **bike**, **push-bike** or **cycle**, is a human-powered or motor-assisted, pedal-driven, single-track vehicle, with two wheels attached to a frame, one behind the other.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A bicycle rider is called a cyclist, or bicyclist.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle was invented in Europe in the 19th century.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] By the early 21st century, there were more than 1 billion bicycles.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles are the principal means of transport in many regions.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They are also popular for recreation, and have been adapted for use as children's toys.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles are used for commuting, shopping, fitness, military and police applications, courier services, bicycle racing, and artistic cycling.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The basic shape and configuration of a typical upright or "safety" bicycle, has changed little since the first chain-driven model was developed around 1885.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] However, many details have been improved, especially since the advent of modern materials and computer-aided design.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These have allowed for a proliferation of specialized designs for many types of cycling.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In the 21st century, electric bicycles have become popular.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle's invention has had an enormous effect on society, both in terms of culture and of advancing modern industrial methods.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Several components that played a key role in the development of the car were initially invented for use in the bicycle, including ball bearings, pneumatic tires, chain-driven sprockets, and tension-spoked wheels.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The first known appearance in English print of the word *bicycle* was in *The Daily News* in 1868, to describe "Bysicles and trysicles" on the "Champs Elysées and Bois de Boulogne".
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The word was first used in 1828 in French to describe a two-wheeled chaise, a horse-drawn carriage.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The design of the bicycle was an advance on the velocipede, although the words were used with some degree of overlap for a time.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Other words for bicycle include "bike", "pushbike", "pedal cycle", or "cycle".
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In Unicode, the code point for "bicycle" is U+1F6B2.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The entity `&#x1F6B2;` in HTML produces 🚲.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The "dandy horse", also called *Draisienne* or *Laufmaschine* ("running machine"), was the first human means of transport to use only two wheels in tandem and was invented by the German Baron Karl von Drais.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] It is regarded as the first bicycle and von Drais is seen as the "father of the bicycle", but it did not have pedals.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Von Drais introduced it to the public in Mannheim in 1817 and in Paris in 1818.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The rider sat astride a wooden frame supported by two in-line wheels and pushed the vehicle along with their feet while steering the front wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The first mechanically propelled, two-wheeled vehicle may have been built by Kirkpatrick MacMillan, a Scottish blacksmith, in 1839, although this claim is often disputed.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In the early 1860s, the Frenchmen Pierre Michaux and Pierre Lallement took bicycle design in a new direction by adding a mechanical crank drive with pedals on an enlarged front wheel (the velocipede).
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Another French inventor named Douglas Grasso had a failed prototype of Pierre Lallement's bicycle several years earlier.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Several inventions followed using rear-wheel drive, the best known being the rod-driven velocipede by Scotsman Thomas McCall in 1869.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In the same year, bicycle wheels with wire spokes were patented by Eugène Meyer of Paris.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The French *vélocipède*, made of iron and wood, developed into the "penny-farthing" (historically known as an "ordinary bicycle", a retronym, since there was then no other kind).
[src:bicycle/bicycle] It featured a tubular steel frame on which were mounted wire-spoked wheels with solid rubber tires.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These bicycles were difficult to mount, dismount and brake due to their high seat over the large front wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In 1868, Rowley Turner, a sales agent of the Coventry Sewing Machine Company (which soon became the Coventry Machinists Company), brought a Michaux cycle to Coventry, England.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] His uncle, Josiah Turner, and business partner James Starley, used this as a basis for the 'Coventry Model' in what became Britain's first cycle factory.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The *dwarf ordinary* addressed some of these faults by reducing the front wheel diameter and setting the seat further back.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This, in turn, required gearing—effected in a variety of ways—to efficiently use pedal power.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Having to both pedal and steer via the front wheel remained a problem.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Lawson, and Shergold solved this problem by introducing the chain drive (originated by the unsuccessful "bicyclette" of Englishman Henry Lawson), connecting the frame-mounted cranks to the rear wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These models were known as safety bicycles, dwarf safeties, or upright bicycles for their lower seat height.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Although, without pneumatic tires, the ride of the smaller-wheeled bicycle would be much rougher than that of the larger-wheeled variety.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Starley's 1885 Rover, manufactured in Coventry is usually described as the first recognizably modern bicycle.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Soon, the *seat tube* was added, which created the modern bike's double-triangle *diamond frame*.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Further innovations increased comfort and ushered in a second bicycle craze, the 1890s *Golden Age of Bicycles*.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In 1888, Scotsman John Boyd Dunlop introduced the first practical pneumatic tire, which soon became universal.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Willie Hume demonstrated the supremacy of Dunlop's tyres in 1889, winning the tyre's first-ever races in Ireland and then England.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Soon after, the rear freewheel was developed, enabling the rider to coast.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This refinement led to the 1890s invention of coaster brakes.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Derailleur gears and hand-operated Bowden cable-pull brakes were also developed during these years, but were only slowly adopted by casual riders.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The Svea Velocipede with vertical pedal arrangement and locking hubs was introduced in 1892 by the Swedish engineers Fredrik Ljungström and Birger Ljungström.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In the 1870s, many cycling clubs flourished.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They were popular in a time when there were no cars on the market and the principal mode of transportation was horse-drawn vehicles.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Among the earliest clubs was The Bicycle Touring Club, which has operated since 1878.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] By the turn of the century, cycling clubs flourished on both sides of the Atlantic, and touring and racing became widely popular.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The Raleigh Bicycle Company was founded in Nottingham, England in 1888.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] It became the biggest bicycle manufacturer in the world, making over two million bikes per year.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles and horse buggies were the two mainstays of private transportation just prior to the automobile, and the grading of smooth roads in the late 19th century was stimulated by the widespread advertising, production, and use of these devices.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] More than 1 billion bicycles had been manufactured worldwide by the early 21st century.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles are the most common vehicle of any kind in the world, and the most numerous model of any kind of vehicle, whether human-powered or motor vehicle, is the Chinese Flying Pigeon, with numbers exceeding 500 million.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles are used for transportation, bicycle commuting, and utility cycling.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They are also used professionally by mail carriers, paramedics, police, messengers, and for deliveries.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Military uses of bicycles included communications, reconnaissance, troop movement, supply of provisions, and patrol, such as in bicycle infantries.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They are also used for fun, including bicycle touring, mountain biking, physical fitness, and play.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle sports include racing, BMX racing, track racing, criterium, roller racing, sportives and time trials.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They are also used for entertainment and pleasure in other ways, such as in organised mass rides, artistic cycling and freestyle BMX.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle has been continually adapted and improved.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Modern materials and computer-aided design have made bicycles safer and more comfortable, and helped to create many more types of bicycle.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles can be categorized in many different ways: by function, by number of riders, by general construction, by gearing or by means of propulsion.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The more common types include utility bicycles, mountain bicycles, racing bicycles, touring bicycles, hybrid bicycles, cruiser bicycles, BMX bikes and electric bicycles.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Less common are tandems, low riders, tall bikes, fixed gear, folding models, amphibious bicycles, cargo bikes and recumbents .
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Unicycles, tricycles and quadracycles are not strictly bicycles, as they have respectively one, three and four wheels, but they are *cycles* and the qualifier "bi" is not used in some other languages, such as "velo" or "fiets".
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A bicycle stays upright while moving forward by being steered so as to keep its center of mass over the wheels, that is in line with the resultant force of gravity and centrifugal force.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This steering is usually provided by the rider, but under certain conditions, may be provided by the bicycle itself.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The combined center of mass of a bicycle and its rider must lean into a turn.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This lean is induced by a method known as countersteering, which can be performed by the rider turning the handlebars directly with the hands or indirectly by leaning the bicycle.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Short-wheelbase or tall bicycles, when braking, can generate enough stopping force at the front wheel to flip longitudinally.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The act of purposefully using this force to lift the rear wheel and balance on the front without tipping over is a trick known as a stoppie, endo, or front wheelie.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle is extraordinarily efficient in both biological and mechanical terms.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle is the most efficient human-powered means of transportation in terms of energy a person must expend to travel a given distance, when travelling slowly or equipped with an aerodynamic fairing.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] From a mechanical viewpoint, up to 99% of the energy delivered by the rider into the pedals is transmitted to the wheels, although the use of gearing mechanisms may reduce this by 10–15% and there is also a small amount of tire slip.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A human traveling on a bicycle at low to medium speeds of about 16–24 km/h (10–15 mph) uses only the power required to walk.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Air drag, which is proportional to the square of speed, requires dramatically higher power outputs as speeds increase.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] If the rider is sitting upright, the rider's body creates about 75% of the total drag of the bicycle/rider combination.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Drag can be reduced by seating the rider in a more aerodynamically streamlined position.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Drag can also be reduced by covering the bicycle with an aerodynamic fairing.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The fastest recorded unpaced speed on a flat surface with a standing start was the hour record in 2016: over 92 km/h (57 mph) with a highly streamlined bicycle.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] One bicycle may have up to a thousand parts.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Most modern bicycles have a frame with upright seating that looks much like the first chain-driven bike.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These upright bicycles frequently have a *diamond frame*, a truss consisting of two triangles: the front triangle and the rear triangle.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The front triangle consists of the top tube and down tube (connected by the head tube), and seat tube.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The head tube contains the headset, the set of bearings that allows the fork to turn smoothly for steering and balance.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The rear triangle consists of the seat tube, with the bottom bracket at the bottom, and paired *chain stays* and *seat stays*, connecting at the rear dropouts, where the axle for the rear wheel is held.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This design, referred to as a *step-through frame* or as an *open frame*, allows the rider to mount and dismount in a dignified way while wearing a skirt or dress.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] While some women's bicycles continue to use this frame style, there is also a variation, the *mixte*, which splits the top tube laterally into two thinner top tubes that bypass the seat tube on each side and connect to the rear fork ends.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These are inherently more aerodynamic than upright versions, as the rider may lean back onto a support and operate pedals that are on about the same level as the seat.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The world's fastest bicycle is a recumbent bicycle but this type was banned from competition in 1934 by the Union Cycliste Internationale.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Historically, materials used in bicycles have followed a similar pattern as in aircraft, the goal being high strength and low weight.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Since the late 1930s, alloy steels have been used for frame and fork tubes in higher quality machines.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] By the 1980s, aluminum welding techniques had improved to the point that aluminum tube could safely be used instead of steel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Since then aluminum alloy frames and other components have become popular due to their light weight, and most mid-range bikes are now aluminum alloy.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] More expensive bikes sometimes use titanium or more often carbon fibre laid-up in resin due to its significantly lighter weight and profiling ability, allowing designers to make a bike both stiff and compliant by arranging the angles of the laid-up fibres optimally.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Virtually all professional racing bicycles now use carbon fibre frames, as they have the best strength to weight ratio.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A typical modern carbon fiber frame can weigh less than 2 pounds (1 kg).
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Wood since the beginning and Bamboo, a natural composite material with high strength-to-weight ratio and stiffness, have been used for bicycles since 1894.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Modern versions use bamboo for the primary frame with glued metal connections and parts.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The *drivetrain* begins with pedals which rotate the cranks, which are held in axis by the bottom bracket.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Most bicycles use a chain to transmit power to the rear wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A very small number of bicycles use a shaft drive to transmit power.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Hydraulic bicycle transmissions have been built, but they can be inefficient and complex.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Since cyclists' legs are most efficient over a narrow range of pedaling speeds, or cadence, a variable gear ratio helps a cyclist to maintain an optimum pedalling speed while covering varied terrain.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Some, mainly utility, bicycles use hub gears with between 3 and 14 ratios, but most use the generally more efficient derailleur system, by which the chain is moved between different cogs called chainrings and sprockets to select a ratio.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A derailleur system normally has two derailleurs, or mechs, one at the front to select the chainring and another at the back to select the sprocket.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Most bikes have two or three chainrings, and from 5 to 12 sprockets on the back, with the number of theoretical gears calculated by multiplying front by back.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In reality, many gears overlap or require the chain to run diagonally, so the number of usable gears is fewer.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] An alternative to chain drive is to use a toothed belt.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These work much the same as a chain, they are popular with commuters as they require little maintenance.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They are slightly less efficient than chains and cannot be shifted across a cassette of sprockets, and are used either as single speed or with a hub gear.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Different gears and ranges of gears are appropriate for different people and styles of cycling.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Multi-speed bicycles allow gear selection to suit the circumstances: a cyclist could use a high gear when cycling downhill, a medium gear when cycling on a flat road, and a low gear when cycling uphill.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In a lower gear, every turn of the pedals leads to fewer rotations of the rear wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This allows the energy required to move the same distance to be distributed over more pedal turns, reducing fatigue when riding uphill, with a heavy load, or against strong winds.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A higher gear allows a cyclist to make fewer pedal turns to maintain a given speed, but with more effort per turn of the pedals.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] With a *chain drive* transmission, a *chainring* attached to a crank drives the chain, which in turn rotates the rear wheel via the rear sprocket(s) (cassette or freewheel).
[src:bicycle/bicycle] There are four gearing options: two-speed hub gear integrated with chain ring, up to 3 chain rings, up to 12 sprockets and hub gear built into rear wheel (3-speed to 14-speed).
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The most common options are either a rear hub or multiple chain rings combined with multiple sprockets (other combinations of options are possible but less common).
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The handlebars connect to the stem that connects to the fork housing the front wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The whole assembly rotates about the steering axis, held by the headset bearings.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] *Upright handlebars*, the norm in Europe and elsewhere until the 1970s, curve gently back towards the rider, offering a natural grip and comfortable upright position.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] *Drop handlebars* "drop" as they curve forward and down, allowing the cyclist to use either a more aerodynamic "crouched" position or a more upright position.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Mountain bikes generally feature a 'straight handlebar' or 'riser bar' with varying degrees of sweep backward and centimeters rise upwards, as well as wider widths which can provide better handling due to increased leverage against the wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Saddles also vary with rider preference, from the cushioned ones favored by short-distance riders to narrower saddles which allow more room for leg swings.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] With comfort bikes and hybrids, cyclists sit high over the seat, their weight directed down onto the saddle, such that a wider and more cushioned saddle is preferable.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] For racing bikes where the rider is bent over, weight is more evenly distributed between the handlebars and saddle, the hips are flexed, and a narrower and harder saddle is more efficient.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Differing saddle designs exist for male and female cyclists, accommodating the genders' differing anatomies and sit bone width measurements, although bikes are typically sold with saddles most appropriate for men.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Suspension seat posts and seat springs provide comfort by absorbing shock but can add to the overall weight of the bicycle.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A recumbent bicycle has a reclined chair-like seat that some riders find more comfortable than a saddle, especially riders who suffer from certain types of seat, back, neck, shoulder, or wrist pain.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Recumbent bicycles may have either under-seat or over-seat steering.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle brakes may be rim brakes, in which friction pads are compressed against the wheel rims; hub brakes, where the mechanism is contained within the wheel hub; or disc brakes, where pads act on a rotor attached to the hub.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Most road bicycles use rim brakes, but some use disc brakes.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Disc brakes are more common for mountain bikes, tandems and recumbent bicycles than on other types of bicycles, due to their increased power, coupled with an increased weight and complexity.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] With hand-operated brakes, force is applied to brake levers mounted on the handlebars and transmitted via Bowden cables or hydraulic lines to the friction pads, which apply pressure to the braking surface, causing friction which slows the bicycle down.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A rear hub brake may be either hand-operated or pedal-actuated, as in the back pedal *coaster brakes* which were popular in North America until the 1960s.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Track bicycles do not have brakes, because all riders ride in the same direction around a track which does not necessitate sharp deceleration.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Track riders are still able to slow down because all track bicycles are fixed-gear, meaning that there is no freewheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Without a freewheel, coasting is impossible, so when the rear wheel is moving, the cranks are moving.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] To slow down, the rider applies resistance to the pedals, acting as a braking system which can be as effective as a conventional rear wheel brake, but not as effective as a front wheel brake.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle suspension refers to the system or systems used to *suspend* the rider and all or part of the bicycle.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This serves two purposes: to keep the wheels in continuous contact with the ground, improving control, and to isolate the rider and luggage from jarring due to rough surfaces, improving comfort.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle suspensions are used primarily on mountain bicycles, but are also common on hybrid bicycles, as they can help deal with problematic vibration from poor surfaces.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Suspension is especially important on recumbent bicycles, since while an upright bicycle rider can stand on the pedals to achieve some of the benefits of suspension, a recumbent rider cannot.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Basic mountain bicycles and hybrids usually have front suspension only, whilst more sophisticated ones also have rear suspension.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Road bicycles tend to have no suspension.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The wheel axle fits into fork ends in the frame and fork.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A pair of wheels may be called a wheelset, especially in the context of ready-built "off the shelf", performance-oriented wheels.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Tires vary enormously depending on their intended purpose.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Road bicycles typically use tires from 25 mm (1 in) to 35 mm (1.4 in) wide, sometimes completely smooth, or slick, and inflated to high pressure to roll fast on smooth surfaces.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Off-road tires are usually wider, from 30 mm (1.2 in) to 100 mm (4 in), and have treads for gripping in muddy conditions or metal studs for ice.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Some components, which are often optional accessories on sports bicycles, are standard features on utility bicycles to enhance their usefulness, comfort, safety and visibility.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Fenders with spoilers (mudflaps) protect the cyclist and moving parts from spray when riding through wet areas.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Germany, UK), fenders are called mudguards.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The chainguards protect clothes from oil on the chain while preventing clothing from being caught between the chain and crankset teeth.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Kick stands keep bicycles upright when parked, and bike locks deter theft.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Front-mounted baskets, front or rear luggage carriers or racks, and panniers mounted above either or both wheels can be used to carry equipment or cargo.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Parents sometimes add rear-mounted child seats, an auxiliary saddle fitted to the crossbar, or both to transport children.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles can also be fitted with a hitch to tow a trailer for carrying cargo, a child, or both.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Toe-clips, toestraps and clipless pedals help keep the foot locked in the proper pedal position and enable cyclists to pull and push the pedals.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Technical accessories include cyclocomputers for measuring speed, distance, heart rate, GPS data etc.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Other accessories include lights, reflectors, mirrors, racks, trailers, bags, water bottles and cages, and bells.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle lights, reflectors, and helmets are required by law in some geographic regions.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] It is more common to see bicycles with bottle generators, dynamos, lights, fenders, racks and bells in Europe.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicyclists also have specialized form fitting and high visibility clothing.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Children's bicycles may be outfitted with cosmetic enhancements such as bike horns, streamers, and spoke beads.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Training wheels are sometimes used when learning to ride, but a dedicated balance bike teaches independent riding more effectively.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle helmets can reduce injury in the event of a collision or accident, and a suitable helmet is legally required of riders in many jurisdictions.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Helmets may be classified as an accessory or as an item of clothing.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bike trainers are used to enable cyclists to cycle while the bike remains stationary.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They are frequently used to warm up before races or indoors when riding conditions are unfavorable.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A number of formal and industry standards exist for bicycle components to help make spare parts exchangeable and to maintain a minimum product safety.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The European Committee for Standardization (CEN) also has a specific Technical Committee, TC333, that defines European standards for cycles.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Their mandate states that CEN cycle standards shall harmonize with ISO standards.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Some CEN cycle standards were developed before ISO published their standards, leading to strong European influences in this area.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] European cycle standards tend to describe minimum safety requirements, while ISO standards have historically harmonized parts geometry.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle industry or cycling industry can broadly be defined as the industry concerned with bicycles and cycling.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] It includes at least bicycle manufacturers, part or component manufacturers, and accessory manufacturers.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] It can also include distributors, retailers, bicycle organizations, bicycle event promoters, and bicycle related service providers.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The global bicycle industry generated sales of $66 billion in 2024.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Over 100 million bicycles are made each year, the top three manufacturing countries being China, India and Taiwan.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In 2025, the global market size was an estimated $116 billion.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Many bicycle brands do not manufacture their own product, but rather import and re-brand bikes manufactured by others, sometimes designing the bike, specifying the equipment, and providing quality control.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] There are also brands that have, at different times, been manufacturers as well as re-branders: a company with manufacturing capability may market models made by other (overseas) factories, while simultaneously manufacturing bicycles in-house, for example, high-end models.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A bicycle can be kept in good condition for decades.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Like all products with mechanical moving parts, bicycles require regular maintenance and replacement of worn parts.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A bicycle is relatively simple compared with a car, so some cyclists choose to do at least part of the maintenance themselves.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Some components are easy to manage using relatively simple tools, while other components may require specialist manufacturer-dependent tools.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Keeping the tires correctly inflated can make a noticeable difference as to how the bike feels to ride.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle tires usually have a marking on the sidewall indicating the pressure appropriate for that tire, from 100 to 1,400 kPa (15 to 200 psi).
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Over the longer term, tires wear out, after 1,500 to 5,000 kilometres (900 to 3,000 miles); with punctures often the most visible sign of a worn tire.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Many community cycling organisations will check brakes and other basic parts for free, or bike shops at low cost.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Disc brakes can be cleaned but may need professional maintenance, but rim brakes are easier to adjust.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Chains can be washed with soapy water then lightly lubricated, but may need replacing after a couple of years.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Other parts, such as derailleur pivot points, can also be lubricated, but lightly as dirt may stick with too much oil.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Very few bicycle components can actually be repaired; replacement of the failing component is normal practice.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The most common roadside problem is a puncture of the tire's inner tube.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A patch kit may be employed to fix the puncture or the tube can be replaced, though the latter solution comes at a greater cost and waste of material.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Some brands of tires are much more puncture-resistant than others, often incorporating one or more layers of Kevlar; the downside of such tires is that they may be heavier and more difficult to fit and remove.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] There are specialized bicycle tools for use both in the shop and at the roadside.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Special, thin wrenches are often required for maintaining various screw-fastened parts, specifically, the frequently lubricated ball-bearing "cones".
[src:bicycle/bicycle] There are also cycling-specific multi-tools that combine many of these implements into a single compact device.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] More specialized bicycle components may require more complex tools, including proprietary tools specific for a given manufacturer.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle has had a considerable effect on human society, in both the cultural and industrial realms.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Around the turn of the 20th century, bicycles reduced crowding in inner-city tenements by allowing workers to commute from more spacious dwellings in the suburbs.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles allowed people to travel for leisure into the country, since bicycles were three times as energy efficient as walking and three to four times as fast.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In built-up cities around the world, urban planning uses cycling infrastructure like bikeways to reduce traffic congestion and air pollution.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A number of cities around the world have implemented schemes known as bicycle sharing systems or community bicycle programs.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The first of these was the White Bicycle plan in Amsterdam in 1965.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] It was followed by yellow bicycles in La Rochelle and green bicycles in Cambridge.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These initiatives complement public transport systems and offer an alternative to motorized traffic to help reduce congestion and pollution.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In Europe, especially in the Netherlands and parts of Germany and Denmark, bicycle commuting is common.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In Copenhagen, a cyclists' organization runs a Cycling Embassy that promotes biking for commuting and sightseeing.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The United Kingdom has a tax break scheme (IR 176) that allows employees to buy a new bicycle tax free to use for commuting.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In the Netherlands, all train stations offer free bicycle parking, or a more secure parking place for a small fee, with the larger stations also offering bicycle repair shops.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Cycling is so popular that the parking capacity may be exceeded, such as in Delft, where the capacity is usually exceeded.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In Trondheim in Norway, the Trampe bicycle lift has been developed to encourage cyclists by giving assistance on a steep hill.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Buses in many cities have bicycle carriers mounted on the front.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] There are towns in some countries where bicycle culture has been an integral part of the landscape for generations, even without much official support.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] That is the case of Ílhavo, in Portugal.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In cities where bicycles are not integrated into the public transportation system, commuters often use bicycles as elements of a mixed-mode commute, where the bike is used to travel to and from train stations or other forms of rapid transit.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Some students who commute several miles drive a car from home to a campus parking lot, then ride a bicycle to class.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Folding bicycles are useful in these scenarios, as they are less cumbersome when carried aboard.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Los Angeles removed a small amount of seating on some trains to make more room for bicycles and wheelchairs.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Some US companies, notably in the tech sector, are developing both innovative cycle designs and cycle-friendliness in the workplace.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Foursquare, whose CEO Dennis Crowley "pedaled to pitch meetings ... [when he] was raising money from venture capitalists" on a two-wheeler, chose a new location for its New York headquarters "based on where biking would be easy".
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Parking in the office was also integral to HQ planning.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Mitchell Moss, who runs the Rudin Center for Transportation Policy & Management at New York University, said in 2012: "Biking has become the mode of choice for the educated high tech worker".
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles offer an important mode of transport in many developing countries.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Until recently, bicycles have been a staple of everyday life throughout Asian countries.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They are the most frequently used method of transport for commuting to work, school, shopping, and life in general.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They also offer a degree of exercise to keep individuals healthy.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles are also celebrated in the visual arts.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] An example of this is the Bicycle Film Festival, a film festival hosted all around the world.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle poverty reduction is the concept that access to bicycles and the transportation infrastructure to support them can dramatically reduce poverty.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] This has been demonstrated in various pilot projects in South Asia and Africa.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Experiments done in Africa (Uganda and Tanzania) and Sri Lanka on hundreds of households have shown that a bicycle can increase the income of a poor family by as much as 35%.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Transport, if analyzed for the cost–benefit analysis for rural poverty alleviation, has given one of the best returns in this regard.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] For example, road investments in India were a staggering 3–10 times more effective than almost all other investments and subsidies in rural economy in the decade of the 1990s.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A road can ease transport on a macro level, while bicycle access supports it at the micro level.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In that sense, the bicycle can be one of the most effective means to eradicate poverty in poor nations.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The safety bicycle gave women unprecedented mobility, contributing to their emancipation in Western nations.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] As bicycles became safer and cheaper, more women had access to the personal freedom that bicycles embodied, and so the bicycle came to symbolize the New Woman of the late 19th century, especially in Britain and the United States.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle craze in the 1890s also led to a movement for so-called rational dress, which helped liberate women from corsets and ankle-length skirts and other restrictive garments, substituting the then-shocking bloomers.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The bicycle was recognized by 19th-century feminists and suffragists as a "freedom machine" for women.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Anthony said in a *New York World* interview on 2 February 1896: "I think it has done more to emancipate woman than any one thing in the world.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] I rejoice every time I see a woman ride by on a wheel.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Willard used a cycling metaphor to urge other suffragists to action.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In 1985, Georgena Terry started the first women-specific bicycle company.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Her designs featured frame geometry and wheel sizes chosen to better fit women, with shorter top tubes and more suitable reach.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycle manufacturing proved to be a training ground for other industries and led to the development of advanced metalworking techniques, both for the frames themselves and for special components such as ball bearings, washers, and sprockets.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] These techniques later enabled skilled metalworkers and mechanics to develop the components used in early automobiles and aircraft.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Wilbur and Orville Wright, a pair of businessmen, ran the Wright Cycle Company which designed, manufactured and sold their bicycles during the bike boom of the 1890s.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In addition, bicycle makers adopted the annual model change (later derided as planned obsolescence, and usually credited to General Motors), which proved very successful.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Early bicycles were an example of conspicuous consumption, being adopted by the fashionable elites.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In addition, by serving as a platform for accessories, which could ultimately cost more than the bicycle itself, it paved the way for the likes of the Barbie doll.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles helped create, or enhance, new kinds of businesses, such as bicycle messengers, traveling seamstresses, riding academies, and racing rinks.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Their board tracks were later adapted to early motorcycle and automobile racing.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] There were a variety of new inventions, such as spoke tighteners, and specialized lights, socks and shoes, and even cameras, such as the Eastman Company's Poco.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Probably the best known and most widely used of these inventions, adopted well beyond cycling, is Charles Bennett's Bike Web, which came to be called the jock strap.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] They also presaged a move away from public transit that would explode with the introduction of the automobile.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Starley's company became the Rover Cycle Company Ltd. in the late 1890s, and then renamed the Rover Company when it started making cars.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Morris Motors Limited (in Oxford) and Škoda also began in the bicycle business, as did the Wright brothers.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Alistair Craig, whose company eventually emerged to become the engine manufacturers Ailsa Craig, also started from manufacturing bicycles, in Glasgow in March 1885.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Now, almost none of them produce their own frames.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Many newer or smaller companies only design and market their products; with the actual production being completed elsewhere, often in Asia.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] For example, over 60% of the world's bicycles are now made in China.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Despite this shift in production, as nations such as China and India become more wealthy, their own use of bicycles is declining due to the increasing affordability of cars and motorcycles.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] One of the major reasons for the proliferation of Chinese-made bicycles in foreign markets is the lower cost of labor in China.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In line with the European financial crisis of that time, in 2011 the number of bicycle sales in Italy (1.75 million) surpassed the number of new car sales.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Emissions related to bicycles come from their production and in actual use from their source of power, that is the food consumed for pedalling, or the electricity required in the case of electric bicycles.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The materials used are mainly steel, aluminium, and carbon fibre.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Compared to other industries, the amounts of materials used are very small and the metals are well recyclable.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A further sources of emissions comes from the rubber pollution from tire wear.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] A study with mountain bike tires measured off-road wear rates per pair of initially 3.6 grams rubber per 100 km, then decreasing to 2 g/1oo km, compared to cars with 11-12 g/100 km per vehicle on-road.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Early in its development, as with automobiles, there were restrictions on the operation of bicycles.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Along with advertising, and to gain free publicity, Albert A.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The 1968 Vienna Convention on Road Traffic of the United Nations considers a bicycle to be a vehicle, and a person controlling a bicycle (whether actually riding or not) is considered an operator or driver.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The traffic codes of many countries reflect these definitions and demand that a bicycle satisfy certain legal requirements before it can be used on public roads.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In many jurisdictions, it is an offense to use a bicycle that is not in a roadworthy condition.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] In some countries, bicycles must have functioning front and rear lights when ridden after dark.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Bicycles are popular targets for theft, due to their value and ease of resale.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] The number of bicycles stolen annually is difficult to quantify as a large number of crimes are not reported.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] About 50% of the participants in the Montreal International Journal of Sustainable Transportation survey were subjected to a bicycle theft in their lifetime as active cyclists.
[src:bicycle/bicycle] Most bicycles have serial numbers that can be recorded to verify identity in case of theft.
